Sequence-to-Sequence (Seq2Seq) – Simple Explanation

Sequence-to-Sequence (Seq2Seq) is a deep learning model that converts one sequence into another sequence.

Input: A sequence of words.
Output: Another sequence of words.

The input and output sequences can have different lengths.

Real-Life Example
English → Tamil Translation

Input:

How are you?

Output:

நீங்கள் எப்படி இருக்கிறீர்கள்?

Here,

Input = English sentence
Output = Tamil sentence

This is a Seq2Seq problem.

Another Example
Input
I love AI
Output
நான் AI-ஐ விரும்புகிறேன்
Why is it called Sequence-to-Sequence?

Because:

Sequence (Input)
        ↓
Deep Learning Model
        ↓
Sequence (Output)

Both input and output are sequences of words.

Architecture

Seq2Seq consists of two parts.

1. Encoder

Reads the input sentence.

Example:

Input

I → love → AI

Encoder converts it into a context vector.

Context Vector

[0.35, 0.82, 0.14, ...]

This vector contains the meaning of the whole sentence.

2. Decoder

Uses the context vector to generate the output sentence one word at a time.

Context Vector
        │
        ▼
Decoder

நான்
 ↓
AI-ஐ
 ↓
விரும்புகிறேன்
Complete Workflow
Input Sentence

I love AI
      │
      ▼
Encoder
      │
Context Vector
      │
      ▼
Decoder
      │
      ▼
நான் AI-ஐ விரும்புகிறேன்

=========


Example – Machine Translation

| Step | Encoder                | Decoder                    |
| ---- | ---------------------- | -------------------------- |
| 1    | Reads "I"              | -                          |
| 2    | Reads "love"           | -                          |
| 3    | Reads "AI"             | -                          |
| 4    | Creates Context Vector | -                          |
| 5    | -                      | Generates "நான்"           |
| 6    | -                      | Generates "AI-ஐ"           |
| 7    | -                      | Generates "விரும்புகிறேன்" |


